  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "In C++, the `-` and `-=` operators serve different purposes, even though they are related since both involve subtraction.\n\n1. **`-` Operator (Subtraction Operator)**:\n   - The `-` operator is the binary subtraction operator, used to subtract two values.\n   - It can also be used as a unary operator for negating a value.\n   - Example of binary usage:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 5;\n     int result = a - b; // result will be 5\n     ```\n   - Example of unary usage:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int negativeA = -a; // negativeA will be -10\n     ```\n\n2. **`-=` Operator (Subtraction Assignment Operator)**:\n   - The `-=` operator is a compound assignment operator that subtracts the right-hand operand from the left-hand operand and then assigns the result to the left-hand operand.\n   - It modifies the value of the variable on the left-hand side.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 5;\n     a -= b; // This will subtract b from a and assign the result to a. Now a will be 5.\n     ```\n\n### Summary:\n- `-` is used for performing subtraction (binary) or negation (unary).\n- `-=` performs subtraction and simultaneously assigns the result back to the left-hand operand.\n\nThis means that `x -= y;` is equivalent to `x = x - y;`, but can be more concise and can also be easier to read in cases where the variable on the left is being modified directly.",
